==Latvian==

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|bat-pro|lv}} {{m|bat-pro|*irā}} ([[cf]]. dialectal, archaic forms {{term|irād|lang=lv}}, {{term|iraid|lang=lv}}, {{term|irāg|lang=lv}}, and also {{etyl|lt|-}} {{m|lt|yrà}}, which existed alongside {{m|ine-pro|*esti}} ([[cf]]. {{etyl|cu|-}} {{term|єстъ|tr=jestŭ|lang=cu}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|есть|tr=jest’|lang=ru}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} dialectal {{m|lt|ẽsti}}, {{etyl|prg|-}} {{term|ast|lang=prg}}), initially with basically existential (“there is”) meaning, but later on extending to all copular meanings, thus replacing {{m|ine-pro|*esti}}. In {{etyl|xsv|-}}, also the first person form {{term|irm||I am|lang=xsv}} is derived from this stem. The origin of {{etyl|bat-pro|-}} {{m|bat-pro|*irā}} is, however, unclear. Various sources have been proposed: an older interjection ([[cf]]. {{etyl|lt|-}} {{m|lt|aurè||look!}}), the particle and conjunction {{term|ir||both... and...|lang=lv}}, a noun with the meaning “existence,” “reality,” “thing,” or even (more recently) the {{etyl|ine-pro|-}} secondary third-person verbal ending {{m|ine-pro|*-r}} with a later ''-ā''-extension.<ref name="LEV">{{R:lv:LEV}}</ref>

====Verb====
