===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|bat-pro|lv}} {{m|bat-pro|*ir}}, from the [[w:Indo-European ablaut|reduced grade]] {{m|ine-pro|*r̥}} of {{etyl|ine-pro|lv}} {{m|ine-pro|*ar||so, then; question particle}} (whence also {{etyl|lv|-}} {{term|ar||with|lang=lv}}, [[q.v.]]). The original meaning “and” ([[cf]]. {{etyl|lt|-}} cognate) is found in 16th- and 17th-century texts, but from the 18th century on {{term|ir|lang=lv}} was no longer used in this sense. Cognates include {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|ir̃|and|lang=lt}}, {{etyl|prg|-}} {{term|ir||also|lang=prg}}, {{term|er||(along) with|lang=prg}}, {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|ἄρα|ἄρα, ἄρ', ῥά|so, then, therefore|tr=ára, ár', rhá|lang=grc}}.<ref name="LEV"/>

